Let <math display="inline">U</math> be a set and let <math display="inline">X \subseteq U</math> then <math display="block">\overline{\overline{X}}= X</math>

== Proof ==
* <math display="inline">\subseteq</math>
** Let <math display="inline">x \in \overline{\overline{X}}</math> then <math display="inline">x \not\in \overline{X}</math>, then suppose <math display="inline">x \not\in X</math> then <math display="inline">x \in \overline{X}</math>, that's a contradiction, so <math display="inline">x \in X</math>. More directly <math display="inline">x \not\in \overline{X}= \left\{ u \in U: u \not\in X \right\}</math> therefore it's not true that <math display="inline">x \not\in X</math> so <math display="inline">x \in X</math>.
* <math display="inline">\supseteq</math>
** Let <math display="inline">x \in X</math> we want to show that <math display="inline">x \in \overline{\overline{X}}</math> 
*** If <math display="inline">x \in X</math> then <math display="inline">x \not\in \overline{X}</math> therefore <math display="inline">x \in \overline{\overline{X}}</math>
